<page>
<title>True / False</title>
<problem>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            (8 points) Suppose <m>A</m> is an <m>m \times n</m> matrix and <m>\vec b\in \mathbb R ^{m}</m> unless otherwise stated. Select <em>true</em> if the statement is true for all choices of <m>A</m> and <m>\vec b</m>.  Otherwise, select <em>false</em>.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="true">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; If <m>A</m> is an <m>n \times n</m> diagonalizable matrix, then <m>A</m> has <m>n</m> real eigenvalues, counting multiplicities. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            True.
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Solution text
        </p>
    </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; If <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb R^n</m> and <m>\vec{y} \in \mathbb R^n</m> with <m>\operatorname{proj}_{W} \vec{y} = \vec{0}</m>, then <m>\vec{y} \in W</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                False.
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>    
        </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="true">`
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; If <m>U</m> and <m>V</m> are <m>n \times n</m> orthogonal matrices, then <m>U + V</m> is also an orthogonal matrix.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                False
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; If <m>\{ \vec{u_1}, \vec{u_2} \} </m> is an orthonormal basis for <m>W</m> and <m>\vec{y} \in \mathbb R^n</m>, then <m>\vec{y} = (\vec{y} \cdot \vec{u_1})\vec{u_1} + (\vec{y} \cdot \vec{u_2})\vec{u_2}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                False
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; Every basis for a subspace can be turned into an orthonormal basis by using the Gram-Schmidt process.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                True
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>True &#160;  / &#160;  False</em>: &#160; If <m>\hat{x}</m> is a least squares solution to <m>Ax = b</m>, then <m>A \hat{x} - b \in \Nul(A^T)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                True
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>

    
    
</problem>


<problem>
    <introduction>
        <p>
           (2 points) Indicate whether the following situations are possible or impossible. 
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Possible &#160;  / &#160;  Impossible</em>: &#160; A <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix with all real eignenvalues, but is not diagonalizable.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                possible.
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution Text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>

    <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <em>Possible &#160;  / &#160;  Impossible</em>: &#160; An orthogonal set of vectors <m>\{ \vec{u_1}, \vec{u_2}, \vec{u_3} \}</m> which is linearly dependent.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                possible.
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution Text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>



</problem>

</page>


<page>


<p workspace="0.5in">
    
</p>

<problem workspace="3in">
    <statement>
        <p>        
            (4 points) Let <m>A = [ \vec{v_1} \text{   } \vec{v_2} \text{   } \vec{v_3} ]</m> be a <m>2 \times 3</m> matrix whose columns form an orthognal set <m>\{ \vec{v_1}, \vec{v_2}, \vec{v_3} \}</m>. Assume that <m>A</m> has at least one pivot. Which of the following statements are TRUE?

            <m>\textit{Select all that apply}</m>
        </p>
        
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li> <m>\| \vec{v_1} + \vec{v_2} \| = \| \vec{v_1} - \vec{v_2} \|.</m></li>
            <li>All of the columns of <m>A</m> are non zero vectors.</li>
            <li><m>\dim ( \operatorname{Col}(A))=2</m>.</li>
            <li><m>\dim ( \operatorname{Row}(A))=1</m>.</li>
        </ol>

    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            Option (a) is correct
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Option (a) is correct.
        </p>
        <p>
            Option (b) is incorrect.
        </p>
        <p>
            Option (c) is incorrect.
        </p>
        <p>
            Option (d) is incorrect.
        </p>
    </solution>

    </problem>
    <problem>

    <statement>
        <p>        
            (4 points) Find the values of <m>a </m> and <m>b</m> so that <m>\vec{v_1}</m> is an eigenvector of <m>A</m> corresponding to an eigenvalue of <m>\lambda_1 = i</m>, where

            <md>
                A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp a \\ b \amp -3 \end{bmatrix} \text{ and } \vec{v_1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 - i \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            
            Also find <m>\lambda_2</m>, the other eigenvalue of <m>A</m>, and an associated eigenvector <m>\vec{v_2}</m>.

            <md>
                a = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ } \text{   } b = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ } \text{   } \lambda_2 =  \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ } \text{   } \vec{v_2} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
            </md>
            
        </p>
        
        

    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m>a = -2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>b = 5</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\lambda_2 = -i</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\vec{v_2} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 + i \end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            solution to a
        </p>
        <p>
            solution to b
        </p>
        <p>
            solution to <m>\lambda_2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            solution to <m>\vec{v_2}</m>
        </p>
    </solution>
</problem>
    
</page>

<page>
<problem workspace="3in">
    <statement>
        <p>        
            (6 points) Fill in the blanks.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>\vec{u}</m> and <m>\vec{v}</m> are vectors in <m>\mathbb R^n</m> with <m>\| \vec{u} \| = 2, \| \vec{v} \| = 3</m>, and <m> \vec{u} \cdot \vec{v} = -1</m>. Determine the length of <m>\vec{u} + 2\vec{v}</m>.
        
        
        <md>
            \| \vec{u} + 2 \vec{v} \| = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
        </md>

        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m> \| \vec{u} + 2 \vec{v} \| = 6</m>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Solution text.
        </p>
    </solution>
</problem>

<problem workspace="3in">

    <statement>
        <p>
            Compute the length of the vector <m>\vec{y}</m>.

            <md>
                \vec{y} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}} \amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{30}} \amp -\frac{2}{\sqrt{24}} \\ \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}} \amp -\frac{2}{\sqrt{30}} \amp \frac{4}{\sqrt{24}} \\ 0 \amp \frac{5}{\sqrt{30}} \amp \frac{2}{\sqrt{24}} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 2 \\ -3 \end{pmatrix}
            </md>
            
            <m>\textit{Hint: Answer is an integer}</m>
        <md>
            \| y \| = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
        </md>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m> \| y \| = 7</m>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Solution text.
        </p>
    </solution>
</problem>

<problem workspace="3in">

    <statement>
        <p>
            Find a non-zero vector <m> \vec{v} </m> so that <m>\vec{v} \in \operatorname{Span}\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 4 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}\right\}^\perp</m>

        <md>
            \vec{v} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
        </md>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m> \vec{v} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            Solution text.
        </p>
    </solution>
</problem>
</page>

<page>
    <problem workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                (2 points) Suppose that <m>A</m> is a <m>5 \times 7</m> matrix such that <m>\text{dim}(\operatorname{Nul} A^T) = 3</m>. Determine the dimension of the column space of <m>A</m>.

                <md>
                    \text{dim}(\operatorname{Col} (A)) = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    \text{dim}(\operatorname{Col} (A)) = 2
                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                (4 points) Let <m>W</m> be a subspace of <m>\mathbb R^3</m> spanned by the orthogonal basis <m>\mathcal{B} = \{ \vec{u_1}, \vec{u_2} \}</m>. Find the projection <m>\vec{x} = \operatorname{proj}_W (\vec{y})</m>. Then determine the coordinate vector <m>[\vec{x}]_{\mathcal{B}}</m> of <m>\vec{x}</m> relative to the basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.

                <md>
                    \vec{u_1} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \vec{u_2} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}, \quad \vec{y} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 7 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <md>
                    \vec{x} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>

                <md>
                    [\vec{x}]_{\mathcal{B}} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\ f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    \vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>

                <md>
                    [\vec{x}]_{\mathcal{B}} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\end{bmatrix}
                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>

</page>

<page>
    <problem workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>    
                (3 points) Determine the least squares solution <m>\hat{x}</m> to the system <m>A \vec{x} = \vec{b}</m>, where

                <md>
                    A = QR = \frac{1}{3} \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \text{     and     } \vec{b} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ -5 \\ 8 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
        
                <md>
                    \hat{x} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    \hat{x} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                (3 points) Give a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>\text{Row}(A)^\perp</m> is spanned by <m>\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}</m>

                <md>
                    A = \begin{pmatrix}  \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp \\  \amp \amp \amp  \amp \\  \amp  \amp \amp \amp \end{pmatrix}
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    A = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>
</page>

<page>
    

    <problem workspace="2in">
