                <md>
                    P =  \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a \amp a \amp a \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }\text{        } D = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a \amp a \amp a \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    P = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}

                </md>
                <md>
                    D = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -6 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
        </problem>

        <problem>


        <statement>
            (4 points) Let <m>W = \text{span} \{ \vec{v_1} , \vec{v_2} \}</m>. Find an <m>\textbf{orthonormal}</m> basis <m>\mathcal{B}</m> for <m>W</m>.

            <md>
                \vec{v_1} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}, \vec{v_2} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ 3 \\2 \end{bmatrix}, \mathcal{B} = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a  \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
            </md>
            
            
            
        </statement>

        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                    \mathcal{B} = \left\{ \frac{1}{\sqrt{17}} \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix},  \frac{1}{\sqrt{21}}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\4 \end{bmatrix} \right\}
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>




</page>
    
<page>
    

    <problem workspace="2in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Show your work problem. Part of the grade is based on the justification/ work shown. Can have parts. E.g.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <statement>
            <p>
                (7 points) In this problem, you will use the least-squares method to find the values <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> which best fit the curve

                <md>
                    y = \alpha x^2 + \beta x
                </md>

                to the data points <m>(-2, 1), (1, 5), (1, 3)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <statement>
            <p>
                What is the augmented matrix <m>\left [ A \ \rvert \ \vec b \right]</m> for this least squares problem?

                <md>
                    \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a \amp a \amp a \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                     \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -2 \amp \rvert \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp  5 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 3 \end{bmatrix}

                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
        </problem>

        <problem>


        <statement>
            <p>
                What is the augmented matrix for the normal equations for this least squares problem?

                <md>
                    \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \amp a \amp a \amp a \\ b \\ c \\ d \\ e \\f  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                     \begin{bmatrix} 18 \amp -6 \amp \rvert \amp  12 \\ -6 \amp 6 \amp \rvert \amp  6\end{bmatrix}

                </md>
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Solution text
            </p>
        </solution>
    </problem>

        <problem>


        <statement>
            <p>
                Find a least-squares solution to the linear system from (a) to determine the parameters of <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> of the best fitting curve.

                <md>
                    \alpha = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }, \beta = \framebox{$\phantom{$\begin{bmatrix} a \amp a \\ b  \end{bmatrix}$}$ }
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                <md>
                     \alpha = \frac{3}{2}

                </md>
                <md>
                    \beta = \frac{5}{2}
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
